// Secrets.xcconfig.example
//
// Copy this file to `Secrets.xcconfig` at the project root (the location
// Xcode is wired to via Project → Info → Configurations) and fill in
// real values. `Secrets.xcconfig` is gitignored anywhere in the tree
// so the real credentials never enter version control.
//
// ## One-time Xcode setup
//
// The xcconfig file has to be wired into the project once. In Xcode:
//   1. Click the `tracker` project at the top of the file navigator.
//   2. Select the project (not a target) and open the **Info** tab.
//   3. Under **Configurations**, expand each configuration (Debug, Release).
//   4. Set the dropdown next to **tracker** (the iPhone app target) to
//      `Secrets` (it will appear once you've added the file to the project).
//   5. Build. The build settings below now reach Info.plist via
//      `$(STRAVA_CLIENT_ID)` substitution, which `StravaService` reads at
//      runtime.
//
// If the file isn't wired up the app launches fine, but Strava connect
// will fail fast with a clear error pointing the user back here.
//
// ## Rotating credentials
//
// If the secret ever leaks (e.g. a checked-in copy in git history), go to
// https://www.strava.com/settings/api → **Reset Client Secret** and paste
// the new value below. All previously-issued user tokens become invalid.

STRAVA_CLIENT_ID = your_client_id_here
STRAVA_CLIENT_SECRET = your_client_secret_here
